  "prompt": "Why and when is it wrong for parents to treat their kids as friends?",
  "response": "Parents treating their children as friends can be problematic for several reasons:\n\n1. When it blurs boundaries\n- Parents need to maintain clear authority and leadership\n- Children require guidance and structure, not peer-level relationships\n\n2. Emotional inappropriate sharing\n- Oversharing personal adult problems can burden children\n- Kids shouldn't feel responsible for parents' emotional well-being\n\n3. Lack of discipline\n- Friendship can undermine necessary parental discipline\n- Children need consistent rules and consequences\n\n4. Developmental needs\n- Children require parents who provide security and direction\n- Friendship dynamics can prevent proper parental support\n\n5. Inappropriate expectations\n- Treating kids as friends might lead to unrealistic expectations of emotional maturity\n- Children aren't equipped to handle adult-level emotional complexity\n\n6. Loss of respect\n- Constant friendship can erode the parent's authoritative role\n- Children may struggle to view parents as reliable guides\n\nAppropriate times for friendship-like interactions:\n- When children become adults\n- During shared activities\n- When maintaining open communication\n- While respecting age-appropriate relationship dynamics\n\nHealthy parenting balances warmth, support, and necessary authority, ensuring children feel loved while understanding parental leadership.\n\nThe goal is nurturing, guiding relationship - not a peer friendship.",
